<TEXT>
environmentalists offered a plan friday 
aimed at preserving ancient forests in the pacific northwest while 
allowing timber companies to cut down more trees 
the federal government has been prevented from selling many older 
forest stands to timber companies because of court injunctions won 
by environmental groups who argued the stands may be the last 
remaining habitat for the northern spotted owl 
the injunctions have drastically reduced the supply of logs for 
lumber mills in the northwest the plan offered friday would release 
490 million board feet of timber currently barred from logging under 
court injunctions 
a compromise plan worked out at a meeting of environmentalists 
timber industry officials and politicians last month went up in 
smoke when some environmental groups said it allowed for too much 
logging 
reaction to the latest proposal was mixed 
im encouraged said rep peter defazio dore i think 
its a thoughtful albeit somewhat complicated response 
but rachel gorlin press secretary to rep less aucoin dore 
said it raises as many questions as it seems to answer 
and jim geisinger president of the northwest forestry 
association said the plan strayed too far from the original 
framework for the summit compromise 
they want to be in charge of managing the national forests 
said geisinger who represented the timber industry at the summit 
i dont think we are prepared to turn that responsibility over to 
them 
overall the environmentalists offer would allow 96 billion 
board feet of federal timber to be harvested in oregon and 
washington over the next 15 months andy kerr conservation 
dirrector of the oregon natural resouces council emphasized at a 
news conference friday that the offer covered only the 1989 and 1990 
fiscal years 
the harvest level is 400 million board feet less than was 
proposed in the plan developed at the june 24 summit although the 
environmentalists called their proposal a minor reduction 
congressional aides who asked not to be identified said the 400 
million amounted to enough timber to supply four mediumsized mills 
with logs for a year 
under the plan 37 billion board feet would be available for 
harvest in national forests the remainder of this fiscal year 39 
billion could be harvested on national forests in the 1990 fiscal 
year and a billion could be harvested on bureau of land management 
land in each of the two fiscal years 
a lot of this was difficult because we are bleeding kerr 
said this plan is not sustainable for timber production and not 
sustainable for spotted owl production 
any longterm plan he said would have to provide more severe 
limits on federal logging with a greater emphasis on improving 
production on private timberland 
the plan would allow harvesting of small fragmented stands 
spotted owl habitat selected by environmentalists and areas that are 
not spotted owl habitat but have been protected by the injunctions 
</TEXT>
