<TEXT>
a homemade bomb exploded outside a 
discotheque in northern honduras early thursday and wounded seven 
american soldiers four of them seriously officials reported 
two other americans in the group escaped injury no one claimed 
responsibility for the fourth attack on us troops in honduras 
since feb 1 
witnesses say the bomb was apparently thrown from a car but 
the scenario is still confused said anne sigmund of the us 
embassy they dont say if the bomb was thrown from a moving car 
or a parked car were still investigating 
the soldiers had gone into la ceiba a coastal town 200 miles 
north of tegucigalpa in civilian dress and without proper leave 
embassy spokesman charles v barclay said 
they were not authorized to go into town he said in a 
telephone interview the group was part of a convoy carrying 
equipment and machinery from puerto castilla to enrique soto cano 
air base i have no further details for the moment 
officials said the convoy of about 150 americans was returning 
wednesday from a roadbuilding exercise with honduran troops and 
stopped at la ceiba for the night puerto castilla is 250 miles 
north of tegucigalpa 
the four most seriously injured soldiers were flown to a military 
hospital in san antonio texas and the other three were being 
treated at soto cano 50 miles northeast of tegucigalpa the embassy 
said 
the names were withheld pending notification of relatives 
col eric sanchez the honduran military commander at la ceiba 
said by telephone the explosion occurred at the lido discotheque 
and four honduran suspects were being questioned he would say 
nothing further about the suspects 
sanchez said the two uninjured soldiers were turned over to us 
officers from the soto cano base because they refused to talk and 
demanded a lawyer the soldiers had been working in the valle del 
aguan 125 miles east of la ceiba barclay said the united states 
has had facilities at the soto cano base in central honduras for 
years and about 1200 us military personnel are assigned there on 
sixmonth rotating tours 
honduras has been the scene of frequent us military exercises 
since 1982 in part as a political signal to the leftist sandinista 
government in nicaragua which borders honduras to the south 
many hondurans resent the increased us military role in the 
central american nation as well as the use of honduran territory by 
ussupported contra rebels battling nicaraguas government 
on april 11 assailants attacked a jeep convoy carrying us 
soldiers outside olanchita near la ceiba one jeep was disabled 
but nobody was injured 
on feb 1 assailants fired at an american military convoy in 
northern yoro province no one was injured 
on feb 18 three american soldiers and two honduran passersby 
were wounded when a bomb was detonated under a passing bus in 
comayagua near soto cano 
a shadowy leftist group calling itself the morazanista national 
liberation front claimed responsibility for all three attacks this 
year and for attacks in 1983 and 1987 
the group formed in 1979 and named after francisco morazan who 
ruled honduras from 1829 to 1832 it is believed to be part of the 
outlawed communist party 
in addition to the attacks on us military personnel other 
violent incidents in honduras have raised fears of increased 
activity by leftwing guerrillas and rightwing death squads 
six people have been assassinated in the last three weeks 
including a university professor shot to death wednesday a union 
leader and a student leader 
on jan 25 former military chief gen gustavo alvarez martinez 
was assassinated he helped found the nicaraguan rebel movement in 
honduras while head of the military from 1982 to 1984 
</TEXT>
