<TEXT>
michael shannon a determined teenager who 
says he left home at 14 forever in hopes of becoming a 
worldclass dancer is coming home to america with moscows 
bolshoi ballet 
five years after he said goodbye to his mother in los angeles 
he is back for a fiveweek crosscountry tour as the only american 
dancer with the bolshoi ballet academy the official school for what 
many consider the worlds most prestigious ballet company 
in the intervening years always without family and usually 
without money young shannon worked and danced his way halfway 
around the world being supported variously by the governments of 
the united states canada sweden hungary and the soviet union 
hes also found himself in finland italy austria 
czechoslovakia and bulgaria and along the way learned to speak 
russian hungarian and italian 
its been in a literal sense a long leap 
its kind of strange shannon said in a backstage interview 
at suburban washingtons wolf trap theater i left home at 14 
forever now i feel like a foreigner coming back home 
when i left my mother said ill miss you and love you but i 
want you to have a better life than i have shannon said i have 
no other family we come from what you would call the lower end of 
the middle class and she had to borrow money for my plane ticket 
the first stop was canada as he traded his southern california 
love of surfing swimming and baseball for a chance to dance i 
still didnt know if id make it he says now 
it wasnt easy even years later when he was discovered by madame 
sophia golovkina director of classical dance at the moscow academy 
choreographic school and a stern but loved master of the ballet 
now in her 70s madame golovkina discovered shannon at a 
ballet competition in jackson miss on one of his brief stopovers 
in this country since moving away 
shes been like a mother to me ever since and worked to get me 
accepted to the bolshoi academy the rigorous training school for 
bolshoi dancers shannon said 
already the recipient of an award from the us national 
foundation for the arts and the first american graduate of the 
hungarian state ballet institute shannon scraped together some 
money packed his bags and ent to moscow 
there was no cultural exchange at that time shannon said 
i was an exchange student without an exchange program and i spent 
every day going from one government ministry to another looking for 
support 
i lived in a hotel and on the last day when i ran out of money 
they called and said you can stay shannon recalled relief 
still clear in his voice 
they dont have any foreigners shannon said of the academy 
which was founded in 1773 and annually draws thousands of young 
soviets hoping to be admitted as students 
although he hasnt been formally admitted to the actual bolshoi 
ballet company shannon hopes to win that honor during or shortly 
after the current us tour the academys first us visit in 20 
years id be the very first american theyve given me so much 
id like to stay for years and bring what ive learned over there 
back here 
the tour will take shannon and company to los angeles where he 
will be able to see and perform for his mother other stops 
include san diego indianapolis madison wis el paso texas 
vail colo binghamton ny and boston 
shannon will dance with a troupe of other young promising ballet 
stars including 21yearold vladimir malakhov and galina 
stepanyenko 23 both winners of gold medals at the recent 6th 
moscow international ballet competition 
both young stars have high hopes for continuing improvement in 
ussoviet relations noting changes miss stepanyenko says are 
being felt all over the world 
it is a difficult process but we have much hope added 
malakhov 
shannon also has hopes and dreams 
with glasnost weve started something really important and i 
want to keep it going where i can ive even danced for president 
gorbachev he was sitting only a few feet from me he said 
i havent danced for my own president he added yet 
