<TEXT>
rustlers are having a field day in maines 
blueberry patches raking up 1 million in purloined berries a year 
but the state is fighting back a new law gives police the ability 
to catch thieves bluehanded 
teams of blueberry thieves who scatter from pickup trucks can 
pick dozens of 24pound boxes in a night according to bob phillips 
president of jasper wyman amp son of milbridge which harvests wild 
blueberries on 7000 acres 
the industry fearing continued thievery during this summers 
harvest turned to the legislature this spring for help 
lawmakers passed a berry bill that was signed into law by gov 
john r mckernan it is designed to give authorities the tools to 
track down the illegal pickers and end the black market make that 
blue market in berries 
the law requires pickers to get written permission of landowners 
and requires anyone who transports 25 pounds or more to get a 
numbered permit from the maine blueberry commission packers and 
shippers must also keep account of the blueberries they receive in 
lots of 25 pounds or more 
finally the law authorizes police sheriffs forest rangers and 
game wardens to make inspections and arrests and investigate 
blueberry thefts 
maine is one of the nations leading producers of blueberries 
and they are one of its largest cash crops blueberries are a 70 
million a year industry in the state according to ed mclaughlin of 
the blueberry commission 
mclaughlin said thefts are worst in seasons when the price is 
highest he estimated the loss during the 1988 season at 1 million 
suspected thieves confronted by wyman employees typically claim 
they took the berries from someone elses fields said phillips 
others spotted in the act make easy getaways on the dirt roads that 
wind through the hilly barrens 
