tropical storm barry was downgraded to a tropical 
depression thursday as it moved across the open atlantic with top 
winds of 35 mph forecasters said 
at 1030 pm edt the depressions center was near 23 degrees 
north latitude and 58 degrees west longitude or 485 miles northeast 
of the northern leeward islands in the lesser antilles 
the system was moving southsouthwest at about 6 mph and was 
expected to continue in that direction through the night turning to 
the west on friday said national hurricane center forecaster hal 
gerrish 
gerrish added that it was rare for a system to regain strength 
once its been downgraded but that if this one does it would not 
threaten any land for at least two to three days 
the depression formed earlier this week off the west coast of 
africa it became the atlantic hurricane seasons second named storm 
when its maximum sustained winds hit 39 mph wednesday 
the seasons first named storm allison caused widespread 
flooding in texas and louisiana last month 
