the discovery that experimental mutant proteins can 
stop the destructive multiplication of the aids virus may give 
scientists a new weapon in their search for drugs to tame the 
disease scientists say 
in reports in todays issue of the journal cell doctors said 
they crafted these proteins by tinkering with two genes of human 
immunodeficiency virus which causes aids 
while one of the researchers called the work a major step 
others were more cautious noting that any practical result of this 
work is probably years away 
some time in the distant future however doctors said these fake 
proteins could be the basis of a cure for acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome 
in the work scientists changed aids virus genes known as tat and 
rev both produce proteins that are essential for the virus to churn 
out new copies of itself inside the body 
the scientists found that by slightly scrambling the genes they 
can make them produce proteins that dont work but because the 
proteins look like the real thing the aids virus is fooled into 
using them instead of its own natural proteins as a result virus 
replication is shut down 
dr maurice green of st louis university experimented with the 
tat gene and dr bryan r cullen of the howard hughes institute at 
duke university worked with the rev gene 
green said that unlike most proteins the fake tat product can be 
taken in by cells there it will jam up the virus control 
mechanism for viral replication 
we are testing it out against the most virulent strains of aids 
virus and we are very encouraged said green its a major step 
forward as far as im concerned in possible aids therapy 
however dr william haseltine of the dana farber cancer 
institute in boston a codiscoverer of both genes cautioned 
its an interesting concept but its a long way from making a 
useful drug 
the aids virus kills by slipping inside blood cells called t 
cells subverting them to make new copies of the virus and then 
killing the cells people eventually die largely because of the 
destruction of these blood cells which are essential for fighting 
routine infections 
the scientists research suggests two possible ways to combat 
aids 
one is to flood the bloodstream with fake viral proteins that 
will overwhelm the genuine product and shortcircuit reproduction of 
the virus the other probably more difficult approach is to 
implant the viral genes that make these bogus proteins into victims 
bodies so they will produce their own antiviral ammunition 
in the latter approach scientists would implant mutant rev or 
tat genes into a patients bone marrow tissue which makes new blood 
cells the new bone marrow would produce blood cells that carry the 
extra viral genes 
when these cells got infected with the aids virus they would not 
be killed instead the added genes would make proteins that would 
keep the virus from reproducing and destroying the blood cells 
you would end up with a population of t cells that are no 
longer sensitive to the hiv virus said cullen at that point 
you will have reconstituted the persons immune system and they 
should be in great shape 
the longterm promise of this technology is that its a cure 
not just a treatment 
but cullen cautioned that this approach is a long long way 
from reality and no one even knows whether it will work 
in the virus the tat gene is a sort of supercharger vastly 
speeding up its ability to make new copies of itself rev is an 
onoff switch when rev is working the virus will assemble the 
proteins it needs to make new copies but when its shut off no new 
virus will be made 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

