the environmental protection agency is stepping 
in with everything but the money to clean up some of the 
worstpolluted military bases nuclear weapons plants and nuclear 
laboratories run by the government 
the epa announced thursday it plans to add 52 sites to its 
national priorities list the socalled superfund list of hazardous 
waste sites needing the most attention 
among the sites are wellknown laboratories and weapons materials 
plants such as fernald in ohio brookhaven in new york oak ridge in 
tennessee savannah river in south carolina and lawrence livermore 
in california military bases account for most of the 52 
estimates for cleaning up the radioactive and hazardous waste at 
all the department of energys nuclear facilities range from 80 
billion to 150 billion 
epa administrator william reilly said in a statement that many of 
the facilities are much larger and more complex than other 
superfund sites with wide varieties of hazardous and radioactive 
wastes 
epa in its superfund program can undertake cleanup activities 
and try to recover the costs from the corporate and other polluters 
when a federal agency gets on the list it must come up with cleanup 
funds out of its budget 
we have not engaged in budgeteering relating to these 
cleanups said jon cannon the assistant epa administrator in 
charge of the superfund when asked about the possible cost to 
taxpayers 
president bushs budget request for fiscal 1990 contains 500 
million for the defense department to clean up its hazardous sites 
although little money may be needed during the beginning 
assessment period which lasts up to two years the costs rise once 
cleanup begins cleanup must begin within 15 months after a plan is 
approved 
you will see budget demands ballooning in future years as 
remedies are selected and the cleanup process the expensive part of 
the process kicks in said cannon 
the epa intervention is nonetheless important cannon said 
the thing about the proposal is that it sets in motion a 
process whereby the federal facility is required to reach agreement 
with epa for cleanup he said once the site is listed it 
becomes a requirement of law that an interagency agreement be 
achieved that a schedule be set that an enforceable program be put 
in place 
the proposed additions to the list are followed by a period of 
public comment after which they become formal 
the 52 sites announced thursday are in 26 states california had 
the most sites 10 followed by alaska and florida each with 
four of the 52 sites 41 belonged to the department of defense 
nine to the energy department one to the transportation department 
