<TEXT>
the seven leaders of the worlds richest democracies 
will spend much of the weekend working in a cocoon of marblecovered 
concrete suspended more than 300 feet in the air 
that is if they dont mistake the openair elevator shafts or 
the tubular artworks adorning the site of the 15th economic summit 
for scaffolding left behind by the builders 
such is the design of la grande arche a 35story white marble 
structure that is one of the french capitals latest architectural 
outrages such is the location for the meetings that run from today 
through sunday 
in attendance will be president bush french president francois 
mitterrand canadian prime minister brian mulroney japanese prime 
minister sousuke uno west german chancellor helmut kohl great 
britains prime minister margaret thatcher and italys prime 
minister ciriaco de mita 
to imagine the structure picture a giant white cardboard box 
standing on its side with the top and bottom flaps folded in to 
form what looks like a deep glassless window frame 
the summit strategy sessions on third world debt the environment 
and aid for eastern europe will be held in the rooftop slab that 
hangs over a cavernous hollow huge enough to hold the notre dame 
cathedral including its spire 
to reach the summit in the sky the leaders will ride the bubble 
elevators that could easily be mistaken for construction staging 
should the statesmen suffer from vertigo they can ascend to the 
meetings through a disorienting expanse of stone stairs that stretch 
330 feet wide at the cubes base 
the arche is not quite finished and its inauguration was 
accelerated to accommodate the prestigious summit 
wittingly or not the planets most influential statesmen will 
serve as the guinea pigs for the controversial new structure which 
will eventually house the ministry of equipment and housing and an 
array of private companies 
hosting the financial summit in a previously unoccupied building 
may ease some security chores and avoid disruption of the business 
activities likely to bustle at the arche once its trapezoidal towers 
are replete with as many as 10000 office workers 
but christening the complex with such a highprofile event could 
also invite embarrassment or disaster 
on the eve of the summit electrical and plumbing problems 
disabled most of the highrises washrooms and elevators proved 
woefully inadequate for the 4500 journalists headquartered in the 
cube plastic dropcloths and wooden walkways still obscured much of 
the courtyard 
walls still needed paint and electricians worked hurriedly to 
test the elevators thursday under the watchful eye of dogs trained 
to detect explosives 
mitterrand personally chose the design submitted by late danish 
architect johan otto von spreckelsen in a 1983 international 
competition for the structure the president deemed the cubic entry 
an effort to unite technical prowess with purity of form 
but in emphasizing form over function the developers have drawn 
fire for what many see as more of an oddity than an artistic 
endeavor 
erected at the western extreme of an imaginary axis extending 
from the louvre through the arc de triomphe and along the champs 
elysees the modernistic marble monument completes the la defense 
cluster of contemporary office towers that many parisians consider a 
wart at the western edge of their revered city 
la defense a bluff beyond the seine and the bois de boulogne 
where the french held off german aggressors in the 1870 
francoprussian war has raised eyebrows and hackles since the first 
ultramodern structures took shape in the architectural 
expressiveness of the 1960s 
 
