<TEXT>
china said today it was imposing tougher rules on 
what books and magazines can publish and there were reports of more 
executions and prison terms in a continuation of the governments 
drive to stifle popular dissent 
a foreign source in chengdu the capital of central sichuan 
province quoted local press reports as saying two men were executed 
last saturday for their actions during deadly riots in that city in 
early june 
the executions which were not reported in the national press 
brought to 29 the number of people known to have been put to death 
for disrupting social order since the june 34 military assault on 
beijing in which at least 200 people were killed 
meanwhile the official peoples daily said today that the state 
press and publications administration has decided to take tough new 
measures to weed out publications it considers unsavory 
it said publishers in recent years have flooded the book market 
with low grade and vulgar material which contain violent murders and 
obscene pornography which have corrupted peoples souls 
it added that books and periodicals to be investigated and 
removed from bookstalls include those with counterrevolutionary 
and bourgeois liberalization propaganda 
the chinese government has blamed the june violence on 
counterrevolutionary rebels trying to overthrow the socialist 
system and has detained or issued arrest warrants for dozens of 
students and intellectuals who led the prodemocracy movement 
books by scholars now on nationwide wanted lists have been 
banned and culture ministry workers have raided private bookstalls 
to seize copies 
the administration said any bookseller or publisher who violates 
the regulations will be fined at least five times the profit made 
the chengdu source said the two executed men zhou xiangcheng and 
wang guiyuan were charged with beating smashing looting and 
burning a catchall of crimes that china uses for rioting neither 
was a student he said 
the chengdu riots of june 45 are believed to be the most violent 
that occurred outside the capital up to 30 people were killed as 
people battled police and a halfblock of the city was destroyed by 
fire more than 100 people were later arrested 
the source said chengdu courts also gave another man a death 
sentence with a twoyear reprieve and sentenced three others to life 
imprisonment one for arson and two for hooliganism the 
twoyear stay of execution means the sentence is converted to life 
if the prisoner shows a proper attitude 
the source said courts in chengdu the past week have sentenced 20 
others to prison terms ranging from five years to life 
in the first weeks following the violence in beijing chinas 
national media reported the arrests of more than 2000 people who 
took part in protests the arrests still are believed to be going 
on although the national press rarely reports them now 
one exception was thursday when television news showed an office 
worker being given a 10year prison term for spreading rumors during 
an interview with abctv 
the interview in which xiao bin 42 of dalian told abc that 
20000 people were killed by troops during their attack on tiananmen 
square apparently was intercepted by china central television when 
abc was sending the unedited tape by satellite 
china tv broadcast the tape and demanded that people turn the man 
in two women reported xiao to police and later received cash 
rewards 
xinjiang radio in chinas westernmost province also reported 
thursday that 10 people had received prison terms ranging from one 
year to life for involvement in a may 19 riot in the provincial 
capital of urumqi 
one man received life imprisonment for a serious case of 
beating smashing and looting during the riot when according to 
official accounts 150 policemen and government officials were 
injured 20 of them seriously and 43 trucks were overturned 
the urumqi disturbances focused on protests over a 
chineselanguage book sexual customs which moslems claimed 
insulted their religion 
about half of chinas 15 million moslems live in xinjiang 
