tests would be conducted in overseas laboratories if south korean 
labs either cannot or will not cooperate 
the first tests will be performed on imported us cherries to 
determine if they contain the chemical daminozide or alar a 
suspected cancercausing agent 
other imported us agricultural products also will be tested 
said song bokyung vice president of the alliance 
meanwhile the ministry of health and social affairs said today 
that recent concerns over food safety would result in more detailed 
testing of all imported food products 
the ministry said laboratory testing on us imported grapefruits 
and oranges showed they contained no alar but it said tests would 
be conducted on other agricultural products such as apple juice 
the alliance recently led a nationwide boycott of florida 
grapefruit after it said a government lab report indicated the 
presence of alar on some fruit although the lab later clarified the 
report to say that its test did not find the chemical consumers 
remained skeptical 
the government lab declined to retest the grapefruit and an 
independent lab said it did not have the equipment meanwhile 
koreas consumer movement against all chemicals in food production 
has grown 
