<TEXT>
the operating rate for us factories fell in 
june to 835 percent while industrial production dropped 02 
percent the government said today further easing concerns about 
inflation but providing more evidence of a slowing economy 
the federal reserve said the june operating rate declined 03 
percentage point from mays 838 percent and aprils 841 percent 
the rate hit a 10year high of 843 percent last december 
declines were widespread throughout the industrial sector with 
especially large drops for autos mining and utilities the 
central bank said 
economists had worried that the steady upward march of operating 
rates last year signaled increased inflationary pressures the 
closer us industry gets to full operating capacity the greater 
difficulty it has producing enough to meet demand leading to 
shortages and price increases 
analysts generally consider an operating rate of 85 percent or 
above as an indication of inflationary pressures 
until recently the central bank has been pushing up interest 
rates in an attempt to cool inflationary pressures without slowing 
growth so much that the economy slides into a recession 
in its other report today the federal reserve said its 
industrial production index stood at 1411 percent of its 1977 base 
34 percent higher than a year ago but down from mays 1414 
percent it was the first decline since it fell 02 percent in 
february which had been the first drop in a year 
the pace of industrial production had risen 06 percent in april 
last months factory operating rate of 835 percent was up from 
830 percent a year earlier 
the operating rate fell 03 percentage point to 838 percent at 
manufacturing plants down from mays 841 percent prior to april 
the rate had declined since it peaked at 847 percent in january 
the rate at factories producing durable goods big ticket items 
expected to last more than three years fell 03 percentage point 
from 827 percent in may reflecting in large part a reduction in 
the production of autos 
the rate at factories producing nondurable goods dropped to 858 
percent comparied to mays 860 percent 
production meanwhile remained flat at manufacturing plants 
making both durable and nondurable goods 
output at mines and oil wells fell 11 percent following a 
revised 03 percent decline in may the june output was 17 percent 
lower than a year ago and analysts said in part reflected the 
effects of a monthold wildcat strike by more than 30000 coal 
miners in appalachia and the midwest 
production at utilities dropped 13 percent in june due in part 
to decreased use of air conditioning because of coolerthannormal 
weather utility production had dropped 02 percent in may 
