<TEXT>
the roman catholic bishop of hong kong has 
appealed for international pressure on britain to offer refuge to 
the territorys people as a safeguard from the uncertain future 
under communist rule 
cardinal john b wu in a letter to about 2500 cardinals and 
bishops seen friday also urged pressure on china to end persecution 
of participants in the crushed prodemocracy movement 
britain has agreed to return hong kong to china in 1997 and 
beijing has promised that the territory can maintain its capitalist 
economy and enjoy a high degree of autonomy for another 50 years 
but the june 34 military suppression of the prodemocracy 
movement in beijing and subsequent crackdown on dissent throughout 
china has led to a loss of confidence in the future among the 57 
million people of hong kong 
these events have shaken not just china but the entire 
world wu said hong kong has felt particularly deeply the 
sufferings of its chinese brothers and sisters 
wu argued that recent events in china have increased anxieties in 
hong kong and he said london had a constitutional and moral 
obligation to provide safeguards for the territorys people 
a right to enter the united kingdom would in no small measure 
help restore peoples confidence in hong kong he said echoing 
arguments made by many of the colonys public opinion leaders 
wu appealed to his fellow churchmen to urge their governments and 
international bodies to use their influence with london to ensure 
that the people of hong kong enjoy all those safeguards from the 
united kingdom which are their right 
hong kong church spokesman rev louis ha said the right to live 
in the united kingdom was such a safeguard 
the british government however has stated it will grant the 
right of abode to only a fraction of hong kong people no details of 
the plan have been released 
