it seeks a softlanding rather than drive the economy into a 
recession as it fights inflation 
its not a question of whether the fed will ease further 
said david jones an economist for aubrey g lanston amp co in new 
york its only a matter of when 
until recently interest rates have risen as the fed tightened 
its grip on credit to slow the economy and stem inflation while 
rates have begun to fall they are still high enough to affect 
spending on durable goods bigticket items expected to last more 
than three years 
durable goods sales were off 13 percent in june after falling 
05 percent in may commerce said besides autos sales of furniture 
and other home furnishings were off 01 percent 
sales of nondurable goods rose 02 percent including a 21 
