<TEXT>
you are 5 years old you are in the hospital and 
about to have surgery for bronchial complications when the child in 
the next bed offers this advice dont cough during surgery or 
youll die 
it happened to ann banks 30 years ago and the memory of that 
moment lingered and sparked the first in a series of books aimed at 
helping kids 8 to 12 years old cope with uncomfortable situations 
the books hospital journal a kids guide to a strange place 
and alone at home a kids guide to being in charge were 
published in june by viking penguin 
there are plenty of story books already out on both of these 
situations but sometimes telling a story just isnt enough or its 
too much the author said in a recent interview 
banks uses a workbook format which allows children to write 
things down learn about them and hopefully gain control of the 
situation 
each year she says about 4 million children enter the hospital 
for an overnight stay for many it is their first hospital visit 
banks recalled that at age 5 she didnt know whether to believe 
her roommates startling claim about the danger of coughing but i 
sure remember being too afraid to ask anyone she said 
as a result the hospital book includes a page titled will it 
hurt and urges readers to ask their doctors and parents to 
describe exactly what will happen to them before during and after 
surgery 
the bood also includes sections on getting to know doctors and 
nurses where children ask their medical people about their favorite 
television shows their hobbies and about why they chose their 
profession 
this way they learn something personal about these people and 
hopefully feel more at ease around them banks said 
banks talked to scores of teenagers doctors nurses guidance 
counselors and specialists 
a section of the hospital book dealing with privacy or more 
accurately the lack of it grew from the interviews with teens 
the kids talked a lot about how embarrassing it was when the 
nurse didnt close the curtain enough or they had to be helped onto 
a bedpan the minute i heard it i knew it was important to 
them 
the result is a section called this is embarrassing which 
urges kids to talk about those indelicate times 
youngsters are encouraged to count the injections they receive 
to ask new people they meet to autograph the book to laugh at 
hospital jokes what do you call a sick alligator an illigator 
the second book alone at home asks children to list the 
locations of firstaid supplies the phone numbers of working 
parents and special people neighbors who a child can turn to 
if problems arise 
with more women working fulltime some experts estimate there 
are 6 million socalled latchkey kids who come home from school 
daily to empty houses 
you tell a child youll be home a certain time and then stop 
off at the grocery store or run some other errand that makes you 15 
minutes late those few extra minutes can seem like a very long time 
for a kid 
each book concludes with a parents guide parents are asked to 
work with their kids in completing the workbooks rehearsing what 
they should do if they lose their keys or if someone knocks at the 
door 
banks who lives in manhattan and is the mother of 5yearold 
kate plans two more books for the series one on divorce and the 
other on living in stepfamilies 
</TEXT>
