<TEXT>
both the factory operating rate and industrial 
production fell last month the government said friday providing 
more evidence of a slowing economy caused by antiinflation measures 
the federal reserve said the june operating rate declined to 835 
percent a 03 percentage point drop from may the rate was 841 
percent in april and hit a 10year high of 843 percent in december 
the fed also said industrial production was off 02 percent last 
month with its industrial production index standing at 1411 
percent of its 1977 base down from mays 1414 percent it was the 
first decline since it fell 02 percent in february which had been 
the first drop in a year 
its really related to the consumer pulling back on autos and 
other durable goods that go with housing said economist david 
jones of aubrey g lanston amp co in new york it was that high 
interest rate environment that was really the major source of the 
weakness 
until recently the fed has been pushing up interest rates in an 
attempt to cool inflationary pressures without slowing economic 
growth so much that the economy slides into a recession 
jerry jasinowski chief economist for the national association of 
manufacturers said fridays reports are not indications of an 
emerging slide into recession 
rather they should be viewed as the temporary softenss that is 
likely to be associated with a softlanding scenario for the 
economy he said 
analysts also saw the decline in the factory operating rate as 
further lessening of inflationary pressures the closer that 
industry gets to full operating capacity the greater difficulty it 
has producing enough to meet demand leading to shortages and price 
increases 
the decline in capacity utilization which reflects increased 
capital investment as well as slower output growth provides 
additional confirmation that contrary to previous fears the economy 
is not in danger of capacity shortages jasinowski said 
robert g dederick of northern trust co in chicago said 
operating rates for iron steel paper and industrial chemicals are 
down 
these are the industries that were so strong earlier and where 
a lot of the inflation was occurring he said 
the manufacturing plant operating rate fell 03 percentage point 
to 838 percent down from mays 841 percent prior to april the 
rate had declined since it peaked at 847 percent in january 
the rate at factories producing durable goods bigticket items 
expected to last more than three years fell 03 percentage point 
from 827 percent in may this reflected in large part a reduction 
in the production of cars 
the rate at factories producing nondurable goods dropped to 858 
percent compared with mays 860 percent 
production remained flat at manufacturing plants making both 
durable and nondurable goods 
output at mines and oil wells fell 11 percent after a revised 
03 percent decline in may production at utilities dropped 13 
percent in june after a 02 percent drop in may 
jasinowski said output of energy materials should increase when 
coal strikes are settled more than 30000 coal miners have been on 
strike for over a month in appalachia and the midwest 
jasinowski also said warmer weather demands for electric power 
would result in increased utility production this summer 
last months factory operating rate was up from 83 percent a year 
earlier the industrial production index was 34 percent higher than 
a year ago 
</TEXT>
