friday the possibility of global warming from the socalled 
greenhouse effect is too much of a risk to ignore 
assistant secretary charles e hess who oversees science and 
education programs said he has named gary r evans as his special 
assistant for global change issues evans has been deputy 
administrator of the departments agricultural research service 
there are climate experts who claim the 1988 drought was 
evidence that global warming has already begun hess said a 
conclusive link has not been proven but the threat of global 
warming from heat trapped by socalled greenhouse gases is too much 
of a risk to ignore 
gases include carbon dioxide chlorofluorocarbons methane 
nitrogen oxides and halons he said in a statement some of the 
gases also seem to be causing a thinning of the highlevel ozone 
layer which filters out a large part of the ultraviolet rays which 
can limite the growth of sensitive crops 
evans will coordinate activities among seven usda agencies and 
