authorizing 466 billion for the state department and allied 
agencies during the fiscal year beginning next oct 1 
reacting to the senate action white house spokesman marlin 
fitzwater told reporters in paris we feel that the united states 
has imposed sanctions that are meaningful and that adequately convey 
our sense of condemnation of the events that occurred in china we 
also believe that we need to be mindful of longterm relationships 
with that country as we move forward 
he said there is a fair degree of unanimity among the united 
states summit partners on the issue 
he said the administration would consider the legislation but 
generally speaking we think we have taken the right course that 
that has been recognized by other nations of the world we feel its 
also supported and recognized by the american public 
mitchell noted that while the amendment requires the president to 
suspend certain trade programs it also has a provision which 
gives him the flexibility to cease any suspension or termination 
if he finds it in the security interest of the united states to 
do so 
the measure adopts several sanctions adopted earlier by the house 
these include sixmonth suspensions of trade insurance by the 
overseas private investment corp and the use of us funds to 
support trade with china 
other sanctions include the suspension of export of satellites 
intended to be launched by china and the suspension of nuclear 
cooperation until the president can certify china is not involved in 
nuclear proliferation 
