<TEXT>
a senator whose father has fought a prolonged 
battle with alzheimers disease introduced legislation friday to 
pump hundreds of millions of dollars into efforts to find a cure 
the legislation would quadruple federal research spending to 500 
million by 1992 and provide additional money for services to help 
victims and their families 
researchers say that one or two additional steps we could 
find that link that might well solve alzheimers disease sen 
larry pressler rsd said at a news conference 
alzheimers an irreversible neurological disease that often robs 
its victims of their memory intellect and ability to communicate 
afflicts 4 million americans and is expected to strike millions more 
as the baby boom generation ages 
two percent of the population between the ages of 75 to 85 have 
the disease and 20 pecent of those over 70 are afflicted officials 
say one of three american families is believed to have an 
alzheimers victim 
the disease has received less attention than aids although it 
affects more people said dom ruscio a spokesman for the 
alzheimers association 
in addition to increasing federal research funding the 
legislation adds three new alzheimers research centers to the 12 
already in the united states the bill also would establish state 
programs with education and support services for victims 
pressler said the legislation identical to a bill introduced 
earlier in the house would finance a research program similar to 
the effort we had for polio in the 1950s 
pressler has witnessed the steady decline of his father tony a 
retired south dakota farmer for 14 years 
pressler is reluctant to discuss his 73yearold fathers 
illness but he wrote in a 1982 magazine article that his father did 
not seem to recognize people and cannot talk 
the disease is especially hard on the families because of the 
constant care victims require and the high cost of their care 
it takes a lot of human resources not only the people 
suffering from it but the people caring for that person pressler 
said 
although the government is spending 120 million a year on 
alzheimers research the effort is highly underfunded said sen 
mark hatfield rore who is cosponsoring the legislation 
