the first emperor is the first imax film made in china and 
the first to place the emphasis on dramatic scenes rather than the 
showy travelogs known to visitors to imax theaters in museums and 
special exhibitions it is a coproduction between the national film 
board of canada and chinas xian film studio which approved the 
script 
the documentary tells of qin shihuang who built the great wall 
of china but whose dynasty lasted only three years after his death 
in 210 bc 
in its retelling of the emperors career the film notes that 
books promoting freedom of thought were burned 
the burning of them enraged the intellectuals of the day qin 
also had a solution for them the narration written by chinese 
screenwriter wang ji cheng says he buried 460 of them alive the 
criticism stopped 
the film otherwise is mostly filled with scenery and pageantry 
which works better in the large imax format than the few intimate 
scenes that tend to be stilted on a screen geared to spectacle 
in addition to the great wall the documentary also shows some 
of the terra cotta army of 7000 lifesize statues that qin left in 
his tomb the site was discovered in 1974 by some workers digging a 
well in shaanxi province and the canadians making the first 
emperor were the first foreign crew allowed to film there 
howells said the collaboration of the canadian and chinese crews 
filming from oct 30 to feb 13 was a big project and not an easy 
task he said however that in retrospect those involved will say 
we didnt have any real major problem 
he attributed most of the difficulties to confusion arising from 
translating and interpreting mistakes or simply cultural 
differences 
wed meet every day at the end of the shoot of that day and 
sort out the problems he said 
as for logistics among the props were 3200 weapons 40 chariots 
and some artifacts from the qin dynasty there were 11 studio sets 
including a sevenstory royal palace and 20 locations nine 
canadians and 368 chinese were working on the first emperor at 
the height of production 
the national film board produced the first imax film for 
montreals expo 67 with imax theres a high focus and ultraclear 
picture and sound comes from many directions seats are in curved 
rows and at a steep incline so viewers get a full perspective and 
are made to feel like theyre actually in the motion picture 
the system since has spread to other countries and more than 60 
theaters now exist to show the films made from outer space to the 
deep sea 
although the national film board takes credit for the idea of 
doing a documentary on qin it says the chinese decided that the 
pageantry and spectacle would be best suited to an imax production 
even though the first theater had yet to be built there 
the first chinese imax theater was planned for beijing 
</TEXT>
