<TEXT>
declining interest rates and increased stock 
activity have boosted activity at wall streets investment houses 
which have struggled in an industrywide recession that has included 
layoffs and restructuring 
much of the renewed optimism which should be reflected in 
improved secondquarter profits at major brokerages is based on a 
return of individual investors to a stock market tarnished by the 
october 1987 crash 
we see much more interest in individual securities whether 
stocks or bonds which obviously would bode well for the industry 
john markese research director for the 110000member american 
association of individual investors in chicago said thursday 
a rise in june in merger activity and in fees generated by 
underwriting new issues of stocks and bonds two key indicators of 
wall streets health should lift industry profits compared with 
the first quarter when some firms lost money analysts said 
without a doubt its going to be one of the better quarters for 
the industry said brenda davis mccoy an analyst with painewebber 
inc 
salomon inc parent of salomon bros earlier this week 
announced that its secondquarter earnings would be the companys 
best ever exceeding the 190 million earned in the first quarter of 
1986 
