<TEXT>
the united states eager to score an initial victory 
for its strategy to reduce third world debt has offered mexico a 
temporary loan of 1 billion to 2 billion to help it close lengthy 
negotiations with commercial bankers 
white house chief of staff john sununu said today that mexico and 
its commercial lenders have some sticky issues to resolve and that 
no deal was in sight 
the quality of the solution is more important than the 
timetable sununu told reporters a few hours before the economic 
summit of seven major industrial democracies opened here 
mexican officials he said want to get it done correctly 
rather than trying to rush it 
bush held a hastily arranged meeting this morning with mexican 
president carlos salinas de gortari who is attending festivities 
marking the 200th anniversary of the french revolution salinas also 
has met with some other summit leaders 
mexico the test case in the new us approach to the third 
worlds 13 trillion debt problem has been holding closely watched 
discussions with its commercial bankers to try to restructure its 
portfolio of foreign loans 
sununu said mexican and bank negotiators were very close on 
terms for an agreement but that they had been stuck on a few key 
points for almost a week 
sununu confirmed a report in todays editions of the new york 
times that to sweeten the prospective deal the united states has 
offered to make a socalled bridge loan to mexico of 1 billion to 
2 billion 
we are ready to do that if it is what is necessary in order to 
complete the agreement he said 
mexico has received similar us loans in the past to ease its 
financial difficulties until fresh assistance from commerical banks 
became available a bridge loan is considered an inducement for 
bankers to make a deal because the new money allows a debtor nation 
to continue meeting its interest payments on foreign loans 
a little more than half of mexicos total foreign debt is owed to 
commercial bankers many of them american institutions 
the united states would like to wrap a deal as soon as possible 
to show its summit partners that its new approach on the debt drawn 
up by treasury secretary nicholas brady can work 
but sununu emphasized that there is no requirement to leave the 
summit with an agreement and that an artificial deadline might 
hurt the quality of the final agreement 
walking into the meeting with bush salinas gestured to reporters 
that a debt agreement was near afterward bush told his mexican 
counterpart let me know on all this other stuff down the road 
the bushsalinas meeting came as more than two dozen leaders of 
rich and poor nations marked todays 200th anniversary of the french 
revolution getting under way this afternoon was the annual economic 
summit of the worlds seven richest democracies the united states 
britain canada france west germany italy and japan 
the combined events have brought together leaders of some of the 
worlds richest and poorest nations although there were no plans 
for them all to sit down together to thrash out world problems 
smaller meetings were planned however to discuss such pressing 
issues as the foreign debt of the developing nations 
egypt india venezuela and senegal wasted no time thursday in 
asking french president francois mitterrand to call a summit of rich 
and poor nations so they can talk about international economic and 
environmental problems 
brazilian president jose sarney also has pressed his countrys 
case with foreign officials 
brazil and mexico are the developing worlds two biggest debtors 
with combined foreign loans of more than 200 billion 
