<TEXT>
the descendants of the log cabins of the american 
frontier are gaining popularity in asia and europe as well as at 
home 
not the roughhewn logs and mudfloored types of yore though 
these are the modern sleek versions made of precisely cut pieces 
of wood and coming equipped with modern conveniences including 
jacuzzis and saunas 
and the increasing popularity of log homes both at home and 
abroad could pep up north georgias forest products industry said 
donald mahaffey president of fireside log homes in ellijay one of 
14 log home makers in georgia and one of the nations largest 
last year fireside produced 250 log homes ranging in price from 
19600 to 42800 and mahaffey estimates that exports of the log 
homes could make up as much as half of firesides volume by 1992 
according to log home living a magazine that tracks the 
industry 452 american log homes were exported last year including 
390 to japan 
overall the us industrys 466 manufacturers produced about 
14353 homes last year 2533 fewer than in 1987 sales by us 
manufacturers increased to 4134 million in 1988 from 401 million 
in 1987 the magazine said 
mahaffey leaves next week for japan to unveil a 1000squarefoot 
log home that fireside developed especially for the japanese market 
the japanese are fascinated with solidwoodwall 
construction said barbara martin program director of the 
building systems council of the national association of home 
builders in washington dc for one thing wood is very scarce in 
that country apparently its a status symbol 
but mahaffey said many americans still perceive log homes to be 
drafty fire hazards that are susceptible to termites 
the industry is trying to change that image officials say log 
homes because they are built of solid wood are able to retard 
fires better than conventionally built houses and a log homes 
thick walls provide better insulation and thus are more energy 
efficient they say 
many of todays log homes are built from machinemade kits 
although a few are still handcrafted 
but john kupferer editor and publisher of log home living warns 
buyers that all log homes require more maintenance than conventional 
houses in the first two years after construction 
until this whole mass of wood settles and shrinks and 
acclimates itself you need to keep the exterior maintained with a 
preservative and you need to keep the cracks filled otherwise they 
fill with moisture he said 
kupferer said the industry is selling larger houses he noted 
that the domestic loghome market is shifting from firsttime home 
buyers to existing homeowners moving up to larger residences 
in the late 1970s and early 80s we built a lot more houses 
than we do today said dewey taylor sales manager at mountaineer 
log homes inc in baldwin which now produces about 50 homes a year 
most of them custommade there was a tremendous amount of small 
cabins then but we have gone from the secondary home to the primary 
residence 
where the typical mountaineer home once was 800 to 1200 square 
feet it now is 1500 to 5000 square feet taylor said we just 
finished one that is 6700 square feet down in snellville he said 
i like wood i like wood interiors said james edward massey 
68 former president of the first national bank of cobb county he 
owns a 1680squarefoot threebedroom two bath log home on 
walnut mountain near ellijay 
a log home breathes massey said and you get better 
circulation and better and even temperatures in a log home 
according to log home livings latest survey most log home 
owners are middleaged collegeeducated professionals who have at 
least two children about 43 percent have annual incomes of more 
than 40000 some 84 percent use their log homes which average 
1872 square feet as their primary residence 
</TEXT>
