<TEXT>
wholesale prices fell 01 percent in june the 
first drop in 18 months driven down by steep declines in energy and 
food prices the government said today 
the slight decline in the labor departments producer price index 
surprised most economists who were expecting a moderate increase of 
03 percent and marked a sharp turnaround from the big 09 percent 
jump in may 
in another report the commerce department said retail sales fell 
04 percent in june their first monthly backtoback drop in more 
than two years as consumer spending remained sluggish 
particularly for cars and other more costly durable goods 
and the federal reserve reported the operating rate for us 
factories fell in june to 835 percent while industrial production 
dropped 02 percent further easing concerns about inflation but 
providing more evidence of a slowing economy 
energy costs which had soared more than 20 percent over the 
first five months of the year fell 31 percent in june the biggest 
drop in three years 
food prices fell 08 percent the steepest in a year and a half 
reversing an identical increase in may 
despite the overall decline economists were likely to read mixed 
signals from the june report because goods other than food and 
energy rose 07 percent the largest increase since october 1986 
because food and energy prices swing widely from month to month 
and are less influenced by the economy as a whole analysts look to 
the inflation rate of other goods as an indicator of underlying 
inflationary pressures in the economy 
despite the drop in the index last month wholesale inflation for 
the first half of 1989 hit a fast 76 percent annual pace nearly 
double last years 4 percent rise 
the labor department said prices of tomatoes and celery which 
had doubled in may fell sharply in june vegetables overall fell 8 
percent last month following a 264 percent rise in may 
other food catagories posting declines in may were pasta 9 
percent fish 73 percent chickens 52 percent and beef and 
veal 38 percent 
prices rose for pork turkey fresh fruit eggs and candy 
energy costs fell across the board with drops of 8 percent for 
fuel oil 4 percent for gasoline and 2 percent for natural gas 
the department said the increase in other categories was driven 
primarily by a 58 percent jump in cigarettes and other tobacco 
products and for ships 
prices for prescription and overthecounter drugs soaps and 
furniture also rose while prices for flatware womens clothing 
jewelry glassware and cosmetics declined 
the overall june decline left the producer price index for 
finished goods one stop short of retail at 1141 meaning that a 
hypothetical selection of goods costing 100 in 1982 would have cost 
11410 last month 10 cents less than in may but 640 more than a 
year ago 
the news from inflation measures earlier in the production 
process was also good the price of intermediate goods fell 02 
percent in june after rising only 01 percent in may while crude 
goods dropped 20 percent following a 09 percent rise an example 
of the three processing stages would be finished bread 
intermediate flour and crude wheat 
most economists believe inflation will continue to moderate over 
the next several months but theyre divided over the longterm 
outlook 
analysts point out that much of the price spurt earlier this year 
was fueled by a onceanddone runup in crude oil prices in the 
spring now that oil has stabilized at the 20abarrel level 
energy prices shouldnt be contributing to inflation for a while 
they believe 
also even though food prices have jumped around a bit this year 
it is clear there will be no repeat of last years drought in most 
of the nations graingrowing regions 
therefore the ppi should remain relatively wellbehaved over 
the next several months predicts economist donald ratajczak of 
georgia state university 
between march 1988 and march of this year the federal reserve 
board fought to curb demand and thus inflation by boosting 
interest rates however the economy has clearly slowed so far this 
year and the fed has permitted interest rates to decline 
early in june and again last week the central bank nudged a key 
interest rate the rate banks charge each other for overnight loans 
down by a quarter of a percentage point 
economist david berson of the federal national mortgage 
association said in advance of todays report that if inflation 
turned out to have moderated last month and if other government 
reports today on retail sales and industrial activity in june 
confirmed the slowing trend fed policymakers might be inclined to 
ease credit another notch before the end of the month 
i think the chances of getting another easing are good but 
just as the fed was cautious in going up theyre going to be 
cautious in coming down berson said 
</TEXT>
