retail sales fell 04 percent in june their 
first monthly backtoback drop in nearly two years as consumer 
spending remained sluggish particularly for cars and other more 
costly durable goods the government reported today 
the commerce department said sales dropped to a seasonally 
adjusted 1408 billion last month following a 01 percent decline 
in may the may figure was revised downward from an 01 percent 
increase originally reported last month sales had risen 04 percent 
in april and 01 percent in march 
it was the first consecutive monthly decline since 1987 when 
sales fell 08 percent in september and 09 percent in october 
retail spending accounts for about onethird of economic activity 
and is closely watched as a measure of the overall economy economic 
growth has been slowing recently prompting concern that federal 
reserve efforts to contain inflation could move the economy into a 
recession instead of the softlanding it seeks 
spending on durable goods big ticket items such as cars and 
home appliances that are expected to last more than three years 
has been particularly affected by the feds credittightening 
measures 
the commerce department said durable goods sales were off 13 
percent in june after falling 05 percent in may and rising 18 
percent in april 
auto sales plummeted 20 percent in june after falling 18 
percent in may it was the biggest drop in auto sales since a 4 
percent decline in october 1987 sales had risen 20 percent in 
april a month of large dealer incentives 
autos represent about 20 percent of total retail sales 
excluding the automotive category overall retail sales rose 01 
percent following hikes of 04 percent in may and 12 percent in 
april 
sales of home furnishings fell 01 percent after rising 11 
percent in may 
sales of nondurable goods rose 02 percent last month the same 
increase as in may they had risen 06 percent in april 
department store and other general merchandise spending was up 
21 percent 
also showing increased sales in the nondurable category was 
apparel sales up 19 percent 
nondurable categories posting declines included food stores 
down 07 percent gasoline stations down 05 percent restaurants 
and bars down 02 percent and drug stores off 03 percent 
for the three months from april through june overall retail 
sales were up 53 percent from the same period in 1988 
