<TEXT>
an italian agribusiness firm said today it will go 
to court to recover losses resulting from an order by the chicago 
board of trade forcing soybean traders from holding positions 
potentially large enough to corner the market 
raul gardini chairman of ferruzzi finanzaria spa made the 
announcement in milan he reiterated the companys position that the 
accumulation of soybean contracts was legal adding ferruzzi and 
all major world traders are convinced that the board made a mistake 
and has to suffer the consequences 
ferruzzi didnt specify the amount of losses suffered as a result 
of the boards order 
but it said damages could be calculated in part as the difference 
between the closing market price of 726 a bushel on tuesday when 
the cbot issued its order and the price during the days through 
july 20 when all soybean traders must reduce their holdings to a 
maximum 1 million bushels 
a spokesman said the suit probably would be filed in chicago but 
did not give a timetable the company also indicated it might seek 
compensation for unrealized profits as well as damage to its 
reputation 
one day earlier a federal judge denied a request by two ferruzzi 
subsidiaries ferruzzi trading international sa and ferruzzi usa 
inc for a restraining order and a permanent injunction ending the 
bots directive 
published reports have said the ferruzzi was the object of the 
directive 
us district judge james zagel on thursday denied the injunction 
request saying the harm to public confidence in the board of trade 
from the injunction would surpass any monetary loss by ferruzzi 
if i grant a temporary restraining order in this case and it 
turns out to be a mistake then a possible default in the market 
a loss of confidence in the market could be a consequence zagel 
said 
cbot karsten mahlmann said zagels decision reaffirms that the 
board of trade has the authority to ensure the orderliness of the 
market and to effect the orderly liquidation of the july soybean 
contract 
soybean futures prices fell in early trading today in reaction to 
zagels ruling the july contract opened at 690 a bushel 7 cents 
below thursdays settlement price 
on tuesday the board of trade the worlds largest market for 
grain and soybean futures issued an emergency order requiring any 
player holding obligations to receive or deliver more than 3 million 
bushels of soybeans for july delivery to reduce those holdings to 1 
million bushels by the end of trading next thursday when the july 
contract expires 
in issuing the order the exchange cited federal regulations that 
allow it to take such action to ensure the orderly expiration of a 
futures contract 
ferruzzis lawsuit claimed it had been irreparably injured by the 
order which it said would diminish confidence in the market and 
hurt us farmers 
in arguments before zagel ferruzzi lawyer james fox said the 
board of trade acted arbitrarily and capriciously and in bad 
faith when it issued the order 
fox noted that the exchange ignored the fact that the market has 
been trading in a very narrow range in recent weeks an indication 
that there was no squeeze or cornering of the market 
john e angle an attorney for the cbot argued that there is 
absolutely nothing in the record to show this action resulted from 
bad faith tantamount to fraud on the part of the cbot 
angle said ferruzzi could appeal the emergency order to the 
commodity futures trading commission which regulates the cbot 
although he refused to grant an injunction zagel said the cbots 
action may not have been totally defensible he said ferruzzi could 
sue and be adequately compensated for any loss in monetary damages 
if it proves its case 
fox said he did not know whether the italian firm would pursue 
the lawsuit or seek monetary damages zagel told attorneys for the 
cbot to file a motion to dismiss the lawsuit by tuesday with a 
response due july 24 
during the hearing before zagel fox said the emergency order 
forced the italian firm to reduce its holdings of july soybean 
contracts by 20 percent on wednesday and another 20 percent thursday 
in related developments the american soybean association called 
for an investigation of the board of trades directive and the 
minnesota agriculture commissioner asked the fbi to check whether 
board of trade officials may have benefited from the effects of the 
order 
soybean futures gained thursday on news that ferruzzi had 
requested the restraining order with the july contract closing up 
10 cents at 696 a bushel the market closed at 726 a bushel 
tuesday before the cbot liquidation order took effect 
